'''Tenman Shrine''' (てんまんじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} ({{ill|lt=Tenmangū|Q798838|WD=Q798838|1=Tenmangū}}) in {{ill|lt=Takayama|Q622594|WD=Q622594|1=Takayama, Gifu}}, {{ill|lt=Gifu Prefecture|Q131277|WD=Q131277|1=Gifu Prefecture}}. It is commonly called '''Murayama Tenjin'''.

=== Outline and history ===
The founding year is unknown. When the army of {{ill|lt=Anejikōji Tadamori|Q56346475|WD=Q56346475|1=Anejikōji Tadamori}}, a mid-ranking {{ill|lt=court noble|Q1196276|WD=Q1196276|1=Kuge}} and military leader in the {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|WD=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}, was defeated in battle, an image of {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}} handed down in his family was enshrined here, and since then the shrine has drawn worship as Tenjingū, deity of learning. However, it is also said that earlier, Hida no Kuni no Miyatsuko Ōyatsuki-no-Mikoto first enshrined Amatsukami here, and thus it came to be a joint enshrinement with Amatsukami. It is also recorded in the {{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}} as a {{ill|lt=candidate shrine|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}} for the shikinaisha {{ill|lt=Ōtsu Shrine (Hida)|Q11437362|WD=Q11437362|lt=Ōtsu Shrine|1=Ōtsu Shrine (Hida)}} (with a possible scribal confusion of Ōtsu/Tsu).

On the {{ill|lt=river terrace|Q1069618|WD=Q1069618|1=Fluvial terrace}} around the shrine is the buried-cultural-property site “Murayama ruins.” In the {{ill|lt=precincts|Q11429002|WD=Q11429002|1=keidai}} is a “Jōmon pit-dwelling site,” remains of a {{ill|lt=pit-house|Q1087793|WD=Q1087793|1=Indicator (genus)}}, designated a Gifu Prefecture {{ill|lt=historic site|Q1081138|WD=Q1081138|1=Historic site}}<ref name="縄文式住居跡">{{Cite web|和書|date=2015-10-15|url=https://www.pref.gifu.lg.jp/page/7296.html|title=Jōmon pit-dwelling remains |publisher=Gifu Prefecture |accessdate=2022-10-19}}</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
*{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amatsukami|1=UNKNOWN}}
*{{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005|1=Sugawara no Michizane}}
*Tatehayatama-no-Kami
*{{ill|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Kami|Q2564508|WD=Q2564508|lt=Ame-no-Koyane-no-Kami|1=Ame-no-Koyane}}

=== Cultural property (historic site) ===
*'''Jōmon pit-dwelling remains''' - The '''Murayama ruins''' around the shrine were excavated in {{ill|lt=1951|Q18591|WD=Q18591|1=1951}} (Shōwa 26){{Sfn|Ōno|Shioya|1960}}, the first case in Gifu where the full structure of a {{ill|lt=Jōmon period|Q52824|WD=Q52824|1=Jōmon period}} {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=pit-house|1=UNKNOWN}} was clarified. From the {{ill|lt=site remains|Q814254|WD=Q814254|1=Feature (archaeology)}}, about 9,700 pottery sherds (estimated 1,118+ vessels) and 200 stone tools were found. Under the name “Jōmon pit-dwelling remains,” it was designated a prefectural {{ill|lt=historic site|Q1081138|WD=Q1081138|1=Historic site}} on February 24, {{ill|lt=1956|Q5221|WD=Q5221|1=1956}} (Shōwa 31)<ref name="縄文式住居跡"/>.

=== Transportation ===
About 25 minutes on foot from {{ill|lt=Kamieda Station|Q5358338|WD=Q5358338|1=Hozue Station}} on the {{ill|lt=Takayama Main Line|Q1188357|WD=Q1188357|1=Takayama Main Line}} of {{ill|lt=JR Central|Q513679|WD=Q513679|1=Central Japan Railway Company}}.

